Task 1.¶

$$ g^{PD}_1 = E_{x_2}(z+x_2)^2 = z^2 + 2z E_{x_2} x_2 + E_{x_2} x_2^2 = z^2 + 2z \cdot 0 + \frac{1}{2}(\frac{1}{3}-(-\frac{1}{3})) = z^2 + 0 + \frac{1}{3} = z^2 +\frac{1}{3} $$

Task 2¶

I chose the MagicTelescope dataset.
Dataset is used for classification of high energy gamma particles in a ground-based atmospheric Cherenkov gamma telescope using the imaging technique.
For more detailed description check
https://www.openml.org/search?type=data&sort=runs&id=1120&status=active

  1. For the selected data set, train at least one tree-based ensemble model, e.g. random forest, gbdt, xgboost.

    I chose random forest.

  1. Calculate the predictions for some selected observations.
  2. Then, calculate the what-if explanations of these predictions using Ceteris Paribus profiles

  1. Find two observations in the data set, such that they have different CP profiles. For example, model predictions are increasing with age for one observation and decreasing with age for another one. NOTE that you will need to have a model with interactions to observe such differences.

In both cases model prediction is negative and is correct.
Both fAlpha and fSize have opposite trends.
Changes are spikey due to the nature of random forest model.

Other variables also behave differently for those samples.

Looking at different faetures We can see that some are very similar, while other differ a lot.
We could investigate how model performs for different ranges of the variables that dont agree.
This could explain the differences in CP.

obs_2 features

  1. Compare CP, which is a local explanation, with PDP, which is a global explanation.

PDP looks siilar to average of CP for 10 samples.

    Both models behave similarly.
    The changes for random forest are smoother than for xgboost.

def classifier_categorical(model, df):
    df.loc[:, df.dtypes == 'object'] =\
        df.select_dtypes(['object'])\
        .apply(lambda x: x.astype('category'))
    return model.predict_proba(df)[:, 1]

explainer = dx.Explainer(model, X_test, y_test, predict_function=classifier_categorical)
